ce:section.ce:para:
Here, we engineered Ce-and Se-doped carbon dots (CS-CDs)-based self-cascading antioxidant nanozymes and utilized them as Cy5-anti-miRNA-155 transfer carriers for inhibiting and imaging the miRNA-155 in M1 macrophages (Fig. 1
                     ). CS-CDs first mimic natural antioxidant enzyme defense systems composed of SOD and GPx to sequentially decompose ·O2
                     − and H2O2. In addition, CS-CDs not only can efficiently promote the transfection of single-strand Cy5-anti-miRNA-155 but also act as a quencher for it, while retaining the inherent red-FL signal of CS-CDs. The Cy5-anti-miRNA-155 inhibits miRNA-155′s biological regulatory function by forming double-stranded hybrids through complementary base pairing with miRNA-155. This enhanced the inhibition of the pro-inflammatory cytokine derived from ROS elimination to drive the M2 macrophage polarization and block the feedback loop between inflammation and ROS, leading to a synergistic RA treatment effect. Meanwhile, the resultant double-stranded hybrid will release from CS-CDs and restore the dye fluorescence (FL) to realize the miRNA-155 ratiometric imaging for accurate RA monitoring via M1 macrophage identification. Both in vitro and in vivo experiment measurements validated the good performance of CS-CDs/Cy5-anti-miRNA-155 (CS-CDs@155) for RA monitoring and synergistic amelioration effect.
